    <descript>
      <abstract> This polygon layer represents the approximate location of real property lots within the District of Columbia.

</abstract>
      <purpose>This data is used for the planning and management of Washington, D.C. by local government agencies.</purpose>
      <supplinf>The Common Ownership Layer (COL) or owner polygons is derived from the following Vector Property Map polygon layers (Tax, Parcel, and Record lots).  Parcels located outside of a Squares boundary and reservations will be added once VPM phase III is complete.  An SDE view or table containing one underlying lot (i.e. Tax or Record) and the many relationship (condos) that were approved for a given lot will accompany this layer.  Additionally, the SDE view or table does not have old lot and new lot fields since often the lot originally approved for the initial condos was subdivided by a later transaction and more condos approved for the various lots created.  Air right lots are not part of the COL layer, but will need to be overlaid against the COL layer to provide users with a true reflection of DC property.</supplinf>
    </descript>

    <logic>Vector Property Map QA/QC

1.) Specifications:

Projection Parameters: Coord. System - NAD83, StatePlane, MD, FIPS 1900, meters.
Correct Extent and Mapping Tolerances: 
Mapping tolerances implicitly define accuracy and precision of the vector feature datasets. 
Min X: 389000, Max X: 408000, Min Y: 124700, Max Y: 147900
Precision: 92563.95 (close to 5 decimals of precision)
Cluster Tolerance: .003048006

2.) QA/QC Steps

Attribute Verification - Database Structure, Domain Values, Field Population
Topological Consistency - Verified Topology against a list of rules, as follows:

Source Checks
Squares were reviewed against their respective source documents (Record Lots- Subdivision Plats, Tax Lots- A&T Plats) and checked for the following:

- Ensure all lots were captured for each square
- Check all lot line dimensions and square footages
- Check for missing building restriction lines on original source plats
- Check for proper lot bearings
- Insure correct units were captured

Squares and Lots Best Fit - Check each squares best fit against the 2002 imagery and ground level features such as curb, sidewalk and buildings.

Errors found during DC QC process were cycled back to vendor until all correction had been completed.</logic>
    <complete>Data mostly complete up to September 2005,  There are remaining issues with the 2005 data that need to be fixed in order to bring the entire dataset current to September 2005.  

The following issues exist in the property data:

1.) Some squares contain COGO linework entered using degress, minutes, and seconds, as opposed to decimal degrees.  This causes spatial inaccuracies that grow as the length of the line gets longer.
2.) Squares with transactions (lot manipulation) that involved an alley/street closing or dedication are not processed.  Parcels that reside outside of a Square(s) boundary are not processed.  Some, although very few Air Rights lots, are processed as part of maintenance.  The layers original date is as of November 2002.  Therefore, in some areas, the data represents property as of September 2005, while in other areas, they still represent property as of November 2002.  Refer to the transaction to discover what areas need edits to bring it to September 2005.
3.) The database is being released with a September 2005 date stamp.  In 2007, work is being done to bring the layer current.
4.) Individual edits that still need to be made are contained in the transcaction table (VPM_transaction).
5.) Alleys, Building restriction lines, Highway Plans, and Easements are captured if they were on the source material.  Source material is active as of November 2002.
6.) Street width is approximate. Users should rely on the published official street widths to set up property lines or determine right-of-way (this is from the DC Land Surveyors Hand Book).  Likewise this should be taking into consideration when doing certain types of GIS analysis utilizing the VP data.
7.) Some Squares are divided by streets. That is, the same Square continues on the other side of the street.
8.) There are areas where record and tax lots overlap.  This occurs mostly due to the following conditions: 1) alley and street deidcations; and 2.) alley and street closings.</complete>
    <posacc>
      <horizpa>
        <horizpar>Since squares are islands and not generated from ground features, staff "best fit" each square to the Earth.  Since there is no citywide Survey Coordinate System, squares are placed in their approximate location.  Once a square was COGO'ed/created it became a "floating islands" without geographic positioning.  Because of this, captured property data had to be positioned relative to other geospatial files that themselves are geo-referenced.  Thus, they were fit to the digital ortho's and planimetrics compiled at a scale of 1:100 or 1" ='s 83.3ft.
Squares were visually positioned over the appropriate area in of the orthophoto and planimetrics (ground level feature were primary source).

For the "best fit" to ortho, 95% of features are within 2 meters of their true position on the 2002 orthophoto.

Within a square, the property map relative accuracy is approximately 2 feet.

- Each Square is an Island, alone unto itself.

- Street width is approximate. The published official street widths to set up property lines or determine right-of-way are correct. There is digital scan information available from DDOT regarding Right-of-Way widths.</horizpar>
      </horizpa>
      <vertacc>
        <vertaccr>A formal accuracy assessment of the vertical positional information in the data set has either not been conducted, or is not applicable </vertaccr>
      </vertacc>
    </posacc>

      <procstep>
        <procdesc>Dataset copied from the cd obtained from Washington, DC 2005

The Office of Tax and Revenue (OTR), RPTA division's public extract was compared against the COL layer once all features were appended.  Similarly, staff ran topology rules (must not overlap self, must not have gaps, area boundary must be covered by boundary of) to detect spatial discrepancies/errors for OS or RPTA to correct, if any errors or omissions are found. 

1.) Staff opened a blank Arcmap document (.mxd) and loaded Tax, Parcel, and Record polygons from the VPM production environment.

2.) Staff created an empty COL feature class (FC) with all fields identified in the participating VPM layers (Tax, Parcel, and Record) as well as the public extract.

3.) Staff used the Object Loader command in Arcmap to initially append Tax and Parcel polygon features to the COL feature class.

4.) Staff performed multiple spatial queries against the COL and Record lot polygons where the layers were selected based on their location (i.e. are contained by, completely contain, are completely within, and contain).

5.) Staff opened the attribute tables of the Record layer and reverse/switch the selection.

6.) Once the reverse and switch selection was made, staff created a temporary field to populate (1 = take).  This is so that staff can query only Record layer features that should be appended to the COL layer (Tax & Parcel have already appended in step 3) by using the query builder inside of the Object Loader.

7.) Staff created  an SSL field (12 character) to populate the SSL based on the truncation of the Square, Suffix, and Lot fields for Tax and Record.   Reservations SSL should lead with "RES " + RESERVATION NUMBER + "0000".  Parcels SSL should lead with "PAR " + PAR + LOT.  SSL's in ITS are currently setup this way.

8.) Staff created a temporary field in OTR's ITS public extract so that non matches could be quantified (i.e. a user can select all records in the public extract that do not have a geospatial match.  Similarly, an ITS Boolean field was also created in the COL layer so that ITS matches can be quantified, where 1 = true and 0 = false.

9.) Staff performed a random visual inspection to spot check and manually select omissions to append to the COL.  This was also done to link the public extract to the various VPM layers to see if any new matches could be identified.</procdesc>
